The paper deals with a wireless distributed computing framework, which involves information exchange over a wireless interference network. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) or Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper focuses on the MapReduce framework, which is a popular distributed computing paradigm, indicating that it could also belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses the tradeoff between computation load and communication load, which suggests that it could belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) or Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories.
